# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1945-detroit-tigers-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1894-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1894 throughout the world.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] The **1900 Detroit Tigers season** was the Tigers' first in the American League, which received recognition as a major league one year later in 1901.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers finished in fourth place out of eight teams with a record of 71–67, 12+1⁄2 games behind Charles Comiskey's Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit's home games were played at Bennett Park.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Outfielder Dick Harley led the team with a .325 batting average, 77 runs scored, and 47 stolen bases.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Sport McAllister led in slugging percentage (.383), and Frank Dillon led in extra-base hits (30).
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Roscoe Miller led the team with a 19–9 win-loss record for a .679 win percentage.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Jack Cronin led in innings pitched (372) and strikeouts (121).
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Burns and George Stallings had spent large sums of money for "releases of star players" and had paid "major league salaries" to the majority of the players.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1901 Chicago White Stockings season** was their first season as a major league team, and their second season in Chicago.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] It was also the inaugural season of American League as a major league.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings had a very balanced lineup, which was led by outfielders Dummy Hoy and Fielder Jones, and scored the most runs in the AL.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] They relied primarily on speed, as Frank Isbell, Sam Mertes, and Jones finished 1–2–3 in stolen bases.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The pitching staff was anchored by Clark Griffith, who went 24–7 with a 2.67 ERA.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The **1901 Detroit Tigers season** was the Tigers' 2nd season in Major League Baseball.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The team was a charter member of the American League, which was originally formed as the minor-league Western League, of which it had also been a charter member.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers finished in third place with a record or 74–61, 8+1⁄2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Most of Detroit's home games were played at Bennett Park, with Sunday games played at Burns Park due to Detroit's blue laws.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Roscoe Miller (23–13) led the team in wins and was the Tigers' first 20-game winner.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] His performance headlined a strong pitching staff that had the third lowest ERA (3.30) in the American League.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Joe Yeager had an ERA of 2.61, for the second best Adjusted ERA+ in the AL, behind Cy Young.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The offense was not as strong however, scoring 741 runs – fifth among the eight teams in the league.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The team's best hitters were shortstop Kid Elberfeld (.308 average) and center fielder Jimmy Barrett (.293 average; 110 runs).
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers had played their games at Bennett Park since 1896, but the graduation to a major league meant that there would now be games scheduled on Sundays, which was forbidden by Detroit's blue laws.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] In order to avoid running afoul of this stricture, owner James D.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Burns built a ballpark on his own property in Springwells Township, Michigan just outside the Detroit city limits.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Named Burns Park, the Tigers would play their Sunday home games there for the 1901 and 1902 seasons.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] During the 1901 season, Detroit attracted 259,430 fans at home and 238,100 on the road, for a total of 447,428.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit ranked third behind Chicago and Boston in overall attendance.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] 1902 was the second year for the **Detroit Tigers** in the newly formed American League.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished in seventh place with a record of 58–77 (.385), 30½ games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The 1902 Tigers were outscored by their opponents 657 runs to 566.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The team's attendance at Bennett Park was 189,469, sixth out of the eight teams in the AL.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit's blue laws prevented the Tigers from playing baseball at Bennett Park on Sundays.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] As a result, the Tigers played their Sunday home games for the season at Burns Park; a stadium constructed by owner James D.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The **1902 Philadelphia Athletics season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The team finished first in the American League with a record of 83 wins and 53 losses.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] In 1902, the Philadelphia Phillies obtained an injunction, effective only in Pennsylvania, barring Athletics' second baseman Nap Lajoie from playing baseball for any team other than the Phillies.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] Lajoie had played for the Athletics in 1901, and appeared in just one game in 1902 before the injunction went into effect.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The American League responded by transferring Lajoie's contract to the Cleveland Bronchos, who were subsequently known as the "Naps" in Lajoie's honor for several seasons.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] Following the A's pennant winning season, the *Philadelphia Inquirer* organized a championship parade for the team through the city on Monday night, September 30, 1902.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The team proceeded in open carriages and were reviewed by Philadelphia Mayor Ashbridge in front of the *Inquirer'*s building on Market Street.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] "There were more than 25,000 base ball enthusiasts from Philadelphia and nearly every town within a radius of twenty miles of the city in the parade.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] A thousand effigies of the "white elephant" were carried by the paraders.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] There were fifteen bands and twenty fife and drum corps in line to furnish music for the marchers." It was estimated that more than 200,000 turned out for the parade.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The **1903 Boston Americans season** was the third season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans finished first in the American League (AL) with a record of 91 wins and 47 losses, 14+1⁄2 games ahead of the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Boston went on to participate in the first World Series held between the AL and National League (NL) champions.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans won the 1903 World Series in eight games over the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team was managed by Jimmy Collins and played its home games at Huntington Avenue Grounds.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Prior to the regular season, the team held spring training in Macon, Georgia.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Cy Young was a coach for the Mercer University baseball team, also based in Macon.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Boston Americans played an exhibition game against Mercer University (with Cy Young pitching for Mercer) on March 23; the outcome being a 13─2 victory for Boston.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team's longest losing streak was three games, which occurred twice; April 20–23 and September 22–23.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team's longest game was 12 innings, which occurred three times.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 13 home runs and had 104 RBIs, and Patsy Dougherty with a .331 batting average.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] It was Freeman's third consecutive season with at least 100 RBIs.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 40 appearances (35 starts) and pitched 34 complete games with a 28–9 record and 2.08 ERA, while striking out 176 in 341+2⁄3 innings.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team had two other 20-game winners; Bill Dinneen (21–13) and Tom Hughes (20–7).
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team had three games end in a tie; July 31 at Washington, August 29 at Washington, and September 25 vs.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Tie games are not counted in league standings, but player statistics during tie games are counted.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Boston had an 11-game winning streak from May 28 through June 8, to put themselves in the AL lead.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] While they briefly fell into second place in mid-June, behind Philadelphia, Boston then won 9-of-10 to recapture the lead, which they held through the end of the season.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans met the Pittsburgh Pirates in the first modern World Series, an agreement between the AL and the NL as a post-season tournament.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The "Amerks" won the best-of-nine series in eight games; after falling behind, 3–1, they won four games in a row, clinching the championship at their home field, the Huntington Avenue Grounds, in Boston.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] The **1945 Detroit Tigers** was the team's 45th season since they entered the American League in 1901.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] The team won the American League pennant on the final day of the season for their fourth pennant in the last eleven years and first since 1940.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] They then went on to win the 1945 World Series, defeating the Chicago Cubs in seven games.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] It was the second World Series championship for the Tigers and first in ten years.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit pitcher Hal Newhouser was named the American League's Most Valuable Player (MVP). for the 2nd consecutive season.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] The catching duties were split between **Bob Swift** (94 games) and **Paul Richards** (83 games).
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Richards got the nod as the starting catcher in the World Series.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Swift took over as the Tigers' manager in 1965 after Chuck Dressen was felled by two heart attacks.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Later that year, Swift was diagnosed with lung cancer and died in October at age 51.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] First baseman **Rudy York** was among the American League leaders in home runs for 11 consecutive seasons from 1937 to 1947, and his .503 slugging percentage as a Tiger ranks #4 in franchise history.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] In 1945, York hit .264 with 18 home runs and 87 RBIs.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] York had a poor World Series in 1945, playing in all seven games, but batting only .179 with no home runs.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Prior to 1944, second baseman **Eddie Mayo** had never hit for a batting average higher than .227.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Yet in 1945, Mayo hit for a .285 average and .347 on base percentage with 24 doubles and a career-high 10 home runs.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Mayo also won his second Gold Glove award in 1945 and led all American League second basemen with a .980 fielding percentage.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Selected for the American League All-Star team, he had the highest batting average among Tigers players with at least 300 at bats.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Hal Newhouser credited Mayo for sparking the Tigers' 1945 pennant drive, calling him the "take-charge guy in our infield." Mayo finished second to Newhouser in the AL MVP voting.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Newhouser had 9 first place votes, and Mayo had 7.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Traded to the Tigers after the 1944 season, shortstop **Skeeter Webb** proved to be a liability at bat, as he hit only .199.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Though he was a fine fielder, many believed he held onto the starting shortstop job despite his weak hitting because he was married to the daughter of Tigers' manager Steve O'Neill.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 7 of the World Series, Skeeter had his best performance, scoring two runs and fielding the final out of the Series.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Third baseman **Bob Maier** played only one season in the big leagues, but he spent that season on a championship team.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Maier played in 132 games for the 1945 Tigers, batting .263 with 58 runs, 34 RBIs, 25 doubles, 7 triples, and 7 stolen bases.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Though he was the starting third baseman during the regular season, the starting job went to Jimmy Outlaw in the World Series, as Outlaw moved from the outfield to third base to make room for Hank Greenberg who had returned from military service in July.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Maier had a pinch-hit single Game 6 of the 1945 World Series, which turned to be his last major league at bat.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Greenberg had missed four seasons to military service, but rejoined the Tigers after his discharge on July 1, 1945.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] At age 34, Greenberg picked up where he left off, hitting a home run in his first game.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Without the benefit of spring training, he returned to the Tigers, was again voted to the All-Star Team, and hit a dramatic pennant-clinching grand slam home run in the 9th inning on the last day of the regular season.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] He also set a major league record with 11 multi-homer games in 1945.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Center fielder **Doc Cramer**, nicknamed "Flit", was a veteran player who had been playing in the major leagues since 1929.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] In 1945, at age 40, he was the oldest player on an old team.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] He hit .275 with 58 RBIs in the regular season and led the team with a .379 batting average in the 1945 World Series, scoring seven runs and batting in four.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Shortly before the 1945 season started, right fielder **Roy Cullenbine** was traded by the Indians to the Tigers.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Cullenbine was raised in Detroit and started his career as a Tiger but was declared a free agent by Judge Landis in 1940.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] In 1945, Cullenbine led the American League with 113 walks and was 2nd in the AL with a .402 on-base percentage.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] He also hit for power in 1945, with 18 home runs (tied with Rudy York for 2nd in the AL), 93 RBIs (2nd in the AL), 51 extra base hits (4th in the AL), and a .444 slugging percentage (3rd in the AL).
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Despite batting only .227 in the Series, Cullenbine walked 8 times for a .433 on-base percentage and scored five runs.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] The starting pitchers were Hal Newhouser, Dizzy Trout, Al Benton, Stubby Overmire, and Les Mueller.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] After winning 20 games in 1943 and 27 games in 1944, **Dizzy Trout** won 18 games in 1945 and was a workhorse in the pennant drive.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] He pitched six games and won four over a nine-game late-season stretch.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 4 of the 1945 World Series, Trout beat the Cubs 4–1 on a five-hitter.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Trout went 1–1 in the Series with an ERA of 0.66.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers #4 starter in 1945 was **Stubby Overmire**.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] He won 9 games and started Game 3 of the 1945 World Series against the Chicago Cubs.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Despite giving up only 2 runs in 6 innings, Overmire took the loss as the Tigers were shut out 3–0.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] After service in the Navy, **Virgil Trucks** returned to the Tigers on the last day of the regular season.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] He got the start in the final game (allowing 1 run in 5+1⁄3 innings), in which the Tigers clinched the pennant.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] To help returning veterans, the Commissioner waived the rule requiring a player to be on the roster on September 1 to be eligible for World Series play.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Trucks was the winning pitcher in Game 2 of the World Series.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Though he had a record of 6–8, pitcher **Les Mueller** appeared in 26 games and played an important role in the 1945 Tigers season.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] After missing the 1942–1944 seasons to military service, Mueller gave up a single to Pete Gray, the St.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Louis Browns' famous one-armed outfielder, in Gray's first major league game in April 1945.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Three months later, on July 21, 1945, Mueller pitched the first 19+2⁄3 innings for the Tigers and left having given up only 1 run.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] No pitcher has thrown as many innings in a major league game since Mueller's feat.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] The game lasted 4 hours and 48 minutes before the game was called due to darkness.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Mueller also pitched 2 scoreless innings in Game 1 of the 1945 World Series.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Relief pitching was split between George Caster (who was selected off waivers from the St.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Louis Browns on August 8, 1945), Walter Wilson, Zeb Eaton, and Art Houtteman.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] The **1945 World Series** featured the Tigers and the Chicago Cubs, with the Tigers winning in seven games for their second championship in six World Series appearances.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] To minimize travel due to wartime restrictions, the first three games were played at Briggs Stadium in Detroit, and the remaining four games at Wrigley Field in Chicago.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Because of the depleted talent pool resulting from many players being in the military, the Tigers and the Cubs both fielded teams which would have been considered mediocre before or after the war.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Warren Brown, author of a 1946 history of the Cubs, commented on this by titling his chapter on the 1945 World Series, "World's Worst Series".
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 1, Detroit ace Hal Newhouser gave up four runs in the first inning and three more in the third.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Pitching for the Cubs in his first of four games in the 1945 Series, Hank Borowy threw a six-hit shutout to defeat the Tigers, 9–0.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 2, Virgil Trucks got the start less than a week after his discharge from the U.S.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Trucks held the Cubs to 1 run, and Hank Greenberg hit a three-run home run in the fifth inning.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers won, 4–1, to even the Series.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 3, the Tigers were shut out by Cubs pitcher Claude Passeau.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Passeau allowed only one hit—a single by Rudy York.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 4, Dizzy Trout helped even the Series, allowing only 5 hits and 1 run.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 5, Hal Newhouser faced Hank Borowy.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Newhouser struck out 9 Cubs, and Hank Greenberg hit three doubles off Borowy.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 6, Hank Greenberg hit a home run in the eighth inning to tie the score, although the Cubs won, 8–7, in extra innings.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] The game ended in the 12th inning with a line drive by Stan Hack which took a bad hop past Greenberg in left field.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Initially, Greenberg was charged with an error, but the call was reversed the next morning, and Hack was credited with a double.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Game 6 is also remembered for Chuck Hostetler's baserunning blunder.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] The 42-year-old Hostetler had debuted the previous year as the oldest rookie in MLB history.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] He reached base in Game 6 on an error to start the 6th inning.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] He advanced to second with one out, and when Doc Cramer hit a single to left field, Hostetler ran through manager Steve O'Neill's stop sign at third base.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] He tried to put on his brakes half way home, lost his footing, fell to the ground, and was tagged out while scrambling around on all fours.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers could have avoided extra innings and won the Series in Game 6 if Hostetler had held up, as he would have scored in the following rally.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Hostetler did not appear in another major league game.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 7, Cubs' manager Charlie Grimm gave the start to Hank Borowy despite his having pitched in Games 1, 5, and 6.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers scored five runs off Borowy in the 1st inning, while Hal Newhouser struck out 10 and held the Cubs to three runs.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] Doc Cramer went 3-for-5, and Paul Richards hit a bases-loaded double in the first inning to clear the bases and give Newhouser a lead.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] In all, Richards had two doubles and four RBIs to lead the Tigers in Game 7.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] The day after the Tigers' Game 7 victory, H.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] A little known fact about the 1945 World Series is teenage boys worked the games as ushers in the stands.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] With most able bodied men away at war, young teenage boys were allowed to work as ushers.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] The boys would line up at the gate outside Briggs Stadium before the game and would be selected in a fashion similar to how migrant workers are selected to work today.
[src:1945-detroit-tigers-season/1945-detroit-tigers-season] The boys would volunteer their services, but would receive tips.
